President Barack Obama has nominated Dr. Rajiv Shah as Administrator of the United States Agency for International Development (USAID). The President praised USAID's accomplishments under the leadership of Acting Administrator Alonzo Fulgham and expressed his gratitude for their work in jumpstarting a $20 billion initiative for agriculture development in food-insecure countries. Dr. Shah currently serves as Under Secretary for Research, Education and Economics and Chief Scientist at the U.S. Department of Agriculture. He has managed various departments within the USDA and has been involved in President Obama's global food security initiative. Prior to his current role, Dr. Shah worked at the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and was involved in health care policy and research. He holds a medical degree from the University of Pennsylvania and a Master of Science in health economics from the Wharton School of Business.